                "htmlBody": "<figure><img alt=\"A handout photo made available by the Philippine Coast Guard (PCG) shows confiscated giant clam shells after the raid\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/A15D/production/_118090314_mediaitem118090313.jpg\" srcset=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/240/cpsprodpb/A15D/production/_118090314_mediaitem118090313.jpg 240w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/320/cpsprodpb/A15D/production/_118090314_mediaitem118090313.jpg 320w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/480/cpsprodpb/A15D/production/_118090314_mediaitem118090313.jpg 480w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/A15D/production/_118090314_mediaitem118090313.jpg 624w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/A15D/production/_118090314_mediaitem118090313.jpg 800w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/A15D/production/_118090314_mediaitem118090313.jpg 976w\"></img>EPA<figcaption>Giant clams can grow larger than one metre across, and weigh up to 250 kg</figcaption></figure>\n<p><b>Around 200 tonnes of illegally harvested giant clam shells worth nearly $25 million (&pound;18 million) have been seized in the Philippines.</b></p>\n<p>The seizure is one of the largest ever hauls of the endangered species.</p>\n<p>Four suspects have been arrested on an island in the ecologically protected province of Palawan.</p>\n<p>Giant clams can grow larger than one metre across, and weigh up to 250kg. They are seen as vital to the local marine ecosystem.</p>\n<p>The Philippines is home to most of the world's giant tropical clam species.</p>\n<figure><img alt=\"Tridacna gigas\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/533D/production/_118090312_mediaitem118090311.jpg\" srcset=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/240/cpsprodpb/533D/production/_118090312_mediaitem118090311.jpg 240w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/320/cpsprodpb/533D/production/_118090312_mediaitem118090311.jpg 320w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/480/cpsprodpb/533D/production/_118090312_mediaitem118090311.jpg 480w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/533D/production/_118090312_mediaitem118090311.jpg 624w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/533D/production/_118090312_mediaitem118090311.jpg 800w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/533D/production/_118090312_mediaitem118090311.jpg 976w\"></img>Getty Images<figcaption>image captionTridacna gigas is the the world's largest clam</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Jovic Fabello, spokesman for the Palawan Council for Sustainable Development, said that the seized shells included Tridacna gigas, the world's largest clam.</p>\n<p>&quot;Taking the giant clams from their natural habitat is a form of inter-generational crime,&quot; he told the AFP news agency.</p>\n<p>&quot;It will permanently affect the marine ecosystem and future generations will be deprived of the benefits accruing from it,&quot; he added.</p>\n<p>Tridacna gigas contain marine algae which are a food source for many of the fish species eaten by humans. They are increasingly vulnerable to poaching, both for their meat and shells, which are used as a replacement for ivory in jewellery and decorations.</p>\n<p>In the Philippines, killing endangered species can lead to prison sentences of up to 12 years and fines of up to a million pesos (&pound;15,000).</p>\n<h2>You may also be interested in: The fishermen destroying coral reefs</h2>\n<figure>   <img alt=\"\" sizes=\"100vW\" src=\"https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg\" srcset=\"https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 320w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 384w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 432w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 480w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 512w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 608w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 640w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 688w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 720w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 768w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 800w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 832w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 976w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 1024w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 1376w,https://c.files.bbci.co.uk/2D48/production/_87229511_boatptc976.jpg 1920w\"></img><video></video><video></video>  </figure>\n<h2>Related Topics</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/c1xp19dn8ret\">Endangered species</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cnx753je2r4t\">Philippines</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/c207p54mdd3t\">Conservation</a></li></ul>\n<h2>More on this story</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-43227969\"><p>'Rare' complete clam fossil fails to sell</p></a><dl><dd>17 March 2018</dd></dl></li><li><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41727132\"><p>Ivory seizures 'hit record levels'</p></a><dl><dd>24 October 2017</dd></dl></li></ul>",
